 ('48', '5', '4', '1', 'en_us', '8', '', '{\"typeId\":\"4\",\"authorId\":null,\"title\":\"Projects\",\"slug\":\"projects\",\"postDate\":1464562037,\"expiryDate\":null,\"enabled\":1,\"parentId\":null,\"fields\":{\"7\":{\"17\":{\"type\":\"project\",\"enabled\":\"1\",\"fields\":{\"heading\":\"Odin\",\"body\":\"<p>Odin is a zsh shell for git focused development. It includes (opinionated) configuration files for git, tmux, as well as vim in order to get you set up in a productive development environment. Check out the project on <a href=\\\"http:\\/\\/github.com\\/tylerreckart\\/odin\\\">github<\\/a>.<br><\\/p>\"}},\"22\":{\"type\":\"project\",\"enabled\":\"\",\"fields\":{\"heading\":\"Tenor\",\"body\":\"<p>Tenor started as an attempt to reconstruct Instapaper with React.js. It was open sourced in the fall of 2015, and I have since taken the repository offline in order to restructure how it works. I am currently rebuilding the application with Elm as well as rewriting and optimizing the HTML Parsing algorithm behind it. I&nbsp;hope to rerelease it by the end of this year. Follow any updates on twitter <a href=\\\"http:\\/\\/twitter.com\\/tylerreckart\\\" target=\\\"_blank\\\">@tylerreckart<\\/a>.<\\/p>\"}}}}}', '2016-06-13 12:19:57', '2016-06-13 12:19:57', '5e87a6ca-d970-4a95-bc71-0585ebdf4361'),
 ('56', '47', '6', '1', 'en_us', '1', '', '{\"typeId\":null,\"authorId\":\"1\",\"title\":\"Terminal Velocity\",\"slug\":\"terminal-velocity\",\"postDate\":null,\"expiryDate\":null,\"enabled\":0,\"parentId\":null,\"fields\":{\"12\":{\"new1\":{\"type\":\"body\",\"enabled\":\"1\",\"fields\":{\"body\":\"<p>I love the command line. So much so that up to 90% of my work is done within the confines of a terminal window. There are countless numbers of editors out there for all systems, but no matter what system I find myself using, I always find myself at home on the command line. It\'s simple, unobtrusive, and fast. And as a developer, these are all things that are immeasurably important to my productivity and workflow.&nbsp;<\\/p><p>The command line itself has been around since the dawn of computing (or at least since the 1950s) and was one of the first ways people were able to interact with computers on a visual level. As a kid, I remember stumbling on the command line and being frightened by it\'s seemingly overwhelming complexity and power over the operations of the computer (mind you, I grew up with Windows 98, ME, and XP). In earlier operating systems like MS-DOS, the command line was your only interface with the computer. It could be used to open applications, games, or run early versions of programs like excel and word processors.<\\/p>\"}}},\"3\":\"Terminal Velocity: Enhance Your Command Line Experience With HyperTerm\"}}', '2016-07-27 15:27:10', '2016-07-27 15:27:10', '49c2985f-7dbd-46cf-bd14-ed41b45b75ac'),
 ('57', '47', '6', '1', 'en_us', '2', '', '{\"typeId\":\"6\",\"authorId\":\"1\",\"title\":\"Terminal Velocity\",\"slug\":\"terminal-velocity\",\"postDate\":null,\"expiryDate\":null,\"enabled\":0,\"parentId\":null,\"fields\":{\"12\":{\"48\":{\"type\":\"body\",\"enabled\":\"1\",\"fields\":{\"body\":\"<p>I love the command line. So much so that up to 90% of my work is done within the confines of a terminal window. There are countless numbers of editors out there for all systems, but no matter what system I find myself using, I always find myself at home on the command line. It\'s simple, unobtrusive, and fast. And as a developer, these are all things that are immeasurably important to my productivity and workflow.&nbsp;<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>The command line itself has been around since the dawn of computing (or at least since the 1950s) and was one of the first ways people were able to interact with computers on a visual level. As a kid, I remember stumbling on the command line and being frightened by it\'s seemingly overwhelming complexity and power over the operations of the computer (mind you, I grew up with Windows 98, ME, and XP). In earlier operating systems like MS-DOS, the command line was your only interface with the computer. It could be used to open applications, games, or run early versions of programs like excel and word processors.<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>And in this time, the command line has largely remained as it was. A simple, colorless window for commands to be executed. But it\'s more than that. The command line is whatever you want it to be. It can be an editor, activity monitor, or even an RSS Reader. If you have the muster to make it, the command line will do it. In recent years, we\'ve also seen a plethora of command line tools around the NodeJS, Ruby, and Python communities to name a few. Some may argue that the command line is perfect the way it is, and yet others disagree.<\\/p>\"}},\"new1\":{\"type\":\"heading\",\"enabled\":\"1\",\"fields\":{\"heading\":\"Enter HyperTerm\"}},\"new2\":{\"type\":\"body\",\"enabled\":\"1\",\"fields\":{\"body\":\"<p>HyperTerm is a unique solution to the problem of extending the potential of the command line. It\'s built with Electron\'s own blend of HTML, CSS, and JavaScript, which makes it accessible to a much larger portion of the developer population that isn\'t experienced with native application development. Github already did this with their own Atom text editor, and proved that&nbsp;applications built with web technologies can be just as fast and performant as their native counterparts. Just like Atom, HyperTerm can be easily plugged into and extended to do anything that the web can do. If you can build the extension, HyperTerm can emulate it. Packages, plugins and themes are already flowing in at a fast pace, and with more than 6,000 stars on Github since it\'s release almost two weeks ago, the packages are only going to keep flowing in and growing in number. I\'ve even contributed a theme and zsh configuration for it myself, and I\'ve got a few more plugins in the works.<\\/p><p>The best part of HyperTerm, to me is the possibility to take a tool that I use for hours on end every day and extend it into the perfect productivity tool for my development workflow.<\\/p>\"}}},\"3\":\"Terminal Velocity: Enhance Your Command Line Experience With HyperTerm\"}}', '2016-07-27 15:47:23', '2016-07-27 15:47:23', '79caa0db-8202-458e-97b1-443cda96179d'),
