 ('1', '20', 'en_us', NULL, '<p>Quisque vel massa gravida, eleifend turpis vitae, fermentum turpis. In hac habitasse platea dictumst. Ut at risus eu turpis sagittis aliquet. Aliquam aliquet metus mattis eros dapibus, sed mattis urna viverra. Integer rutrum sodales ornare. Integer sed lacinia nulla. Maecenas mattis sagittis congue. Sed ac turpis et risus pulvinar condimentum.</p>', NULL, '2016-05-30 21:59:47', '2016-05-31 16:57:21', 'cf2853c6-6953-42a6-acb4-327d0d92ce12'),
 ('3', '23', 'en_us', NULL, '<p>Great teams are built on the principles of learning and collaboration and you’ll often find developers that have a deep understanding of design principles, and designers that aren’t afraid to sit in front of an editor and hack away. Generalists, in the web design world are a unique mixture of design and development, leading to a better understanding of the nuances of our respective crafts and in turn, better collaboration.</p>\n\n<p>For the first few years of my career I solely defined myself as a designer. I worked on everything from interfaces to branding, and while I had a working knowledge of HTML and CSS, that’s as far as my engineering experienced stretched.</p>\n\n\n\n<p>For a couple of years, that’s all the experience that I needed; then things changed. I started to feel like the work I was doing wasn’t good enough. No matter how hard I worked or how many hours I put in, it just wasn’t enough. I got frustrated with the industry and burnt out. I decided to take some time off, which would slowly turn from a little time off into a few years off. I pursued other opportunities, went to college, left college, and eventually found myself right back where I had started.</p>\n\n\n\n<p>I was at a crossroads. During the time that I wasn’t actively working in the tech industry I still kept up on emerging practices and technologies. I had seen the internet evolve over those few years. I watched the rise of frameworks like React and Angular. I saw as JavaScript went from being a utility language to dominating the face of frontend development. It was like I was standing at the top of a waterfall, I could continue to observe, or I could take a risk and jump in.</p>\n\n\n\n<p>I jumped in and fell in love.</p>\n\n\n\n<p>Code went from being a clunky way of making my designs functional to being at the core of what I do. While I may no longer spend my days deep in the depths of interfaces or manipulating paths at 6400% to get an icon just right, I still incorporate the foundations of design that I learned all those years ago into my everyday work. My experience as a designer has immeasurably influenced the way I work as a developer. For years the trope in the the industry has been for designers to learn to code, but that’s only half of the problem. Developers need to understand design principles, too. Understanding what we do from both sides has benefits that go way beyond being able to mock up a webpage or interface element in Sketch.</p>\n\n\n\n<p>Focusing on improving our non-technical skills is how we become better developers. Having insight into why a particular design decision was made allows us to adapt the way we write software for the demands of each unique problem that we may face along the way. The same goes for designers. Nothing is more toxic to the outcome of a project than conflicts between the design and development teams. Conflict is like a brick wall in our industry, and in far too many teams that wall is an immovable object surrounded on either side by an unstoppable force.</p>\n\n\n\n<p>Understanding each other’s point of view allows us to work together. It encourages us to tear down that wall, brick by brick, until no barriers remain. Understanding is the gateway to collaboration, discussion, and teamwork, which enables us to have fun and productive discussions that lead to unique experiences, innovative features, and a better final product. Most of all, it enables us to love what we do. And the more we love what we do, the less we are at risk for burning out. And trust me, it’s not fun.</p>\n\n\n\n<p>At Authentic Form &amp; Function, we embrace the the concept of the generalist. We all wear many hats, and you can see that through our work. Helping clients understand the unique problems and solutions to their projects will not only lead to better communication, but to better collaboration on both sides. Great designers and developers alike know that creativity is at the cornerstone of what they do. Embrace your creativity. Learn what your colleagues think. Discuss, collaborate, and make. Do this and an endless number of doors will open.</p>\n\n<hr /><p><em>This post originally appeared on the <a href=\"http://authenticff.com/journal\" target=\"_blank\">Authentic Form &amp; Function</a> journal</em><em>.</em><br /></p>', NULL, '2016-06-02 00:25:44', '2016-06-02 00:30:38', '8685aec1-7549-4635-8e82-da5e8685c2ea'),
 ('5', '25', 'en_us', NULL, '<p>Tyler Reckart is a <a href=\"http://github.com/tylerreckart\">front-end developer</a> and <a href=\"http://dribbble.com/tylerreckart\">designer</a>. He thinks a lot about how to build tools that <a href=\"http://github.com/tylerreckart/odin\">improve your workflow</a> and increase productivity. He works a lot with languages like JavaScript, PHP, Twig, and Elm, and is constantly continuing his education exploring new languages and tools. <em>He is currently making his way through the world of functional programming through Haskell.</em> <br /></p>\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n<p>Tyler started his career as a self-taught designer, working primarily on mobile/web interfaces. The skills that he accumulated working on freelance projects landed him a role with <a href=\"http://qui.lt\">Quilt</a> along side their creative director to help bring the company\'s vision to life. Quilt was, in a time before privacy was the standard among social media platforms, an innovative social network that helped to pave the way for privacy in social media. </p>\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n<p>After parting ways with the Quilt team, he shifted his focus from design to his studies, and decided to take a hiatus from the tech industry. In that time he focused on studying the nature of mathematics and philosophy. A few years passed, and he returned to the industry reinvigorated and with a passion for software development. </p>\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n<p>He currently is working with the awesome team at <a href=\"http://authenticff.com\">Authentic Form &amp; Function</a>, working with companies to turn their visions for the web into a reality while helping to shape and promote the principals of remote work. While he isn\'t sitting behind a keyboard or writing about himself the third person, he enjoys carving through the streets of Greenville, South Carolina on the wheels of a skateboard and building his ever-growing collection of comic books.  </p>', NULL, '2016-06-02 23:22:19', '2016-06-04 18:18:07', '4ae298ca-b1ff-4008-be46-76fdf7db7634'),
 ('6', '26', 'en_us', 'About the site', NULL, NULL, '2016-06-02 23:22:19', '2016-06-04 18:18:07', '5a268055-97f2-45dc-bcc5-4712a3eb9923'),
 ('7', '27', 'en_us', NULL, '<p>This URL has been the home for my online presence for many years. It\'s gone through several phases. At times it has been a blog, at others a portfolio. The current design was created with simplicity in mind. It serves as an outlet for my design and development related thoughts as well as the occasional cross-post from my company\'s journal on remote work/life/balance.</p>\n\n<p>In case you were wondering, this site is:</p>\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n<ul><li>Designed and built on a Macbook Pro in Greenville, South Carolina</li><li>Coded with Vim</li><li>Built on <a href=\"http://craftcms.com\">Craft</a>, an open source no-nonsense CMS</li><li>Hosted on a custom <a href=\"http://linode.com\">Linode</a> server</li><li>99% <a href=\"https://github.com/tylerreckart/tylerreckart.com\">open source</a></li></ul><p>The 1% of the site that isn\'t open source has to do with a few deployment scripts and files that would contain sensitive data for accessing my server. I think you can understand why I wouldn\'t want that out in the open.</p>\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n<p>For questions, comments, or inquiries, please contact me on <a href=\"http://twitter.com/tylerreckart\">Twitter</a>. Though, if you\'d rather do it the old fashioned way, I can be reached via email at tyler dot reckart at gmail dot com. </p>', NULL, '2016-06-02 23:22:19', '2016-06-04 18:18:07', 'e3c0b40a-0086-4d52-afe4-f36108dfd3bb'),
 ('20', '48', 'en_us', NULL, '<p>I love the command line. So much so that up to 90% of my work is done within the confines of a terminal window. There are countless numbers of editors out there for all systems, but no matter what system I find myself using, I always find myself at home on the command line. It\'s simple, unobtrusive, and fast. And as a developer, these are all things that are immeasurably important to my productivity and workflow. </p>\n\n<p>The command line itself has been around since the dawn of computing (or at least since the 1950s) and was one of the first ways people were able to interact with computers on a visual level. As a kid, I remember stumbling on the command line and being frightened by it\'s seemingly overwhelming complexity and power over the operations of the computer (mind you, I grew up with Windows 98, ME, and XP). In earlier operating systems like MS-DOS, the command line was your only interface with the computer. It could be used to open applications, games, or run early versions of programs like excel and word processors.</p>\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n<p>And in this time, the command line has largely remained as it was. A simple, colorless window for commands to be executed. But it\'s more than that. The command line is whatever you want it to be. It can be an editor, activity monitor, or even an RSS Reader. If you have the muster to make it, the command line will do it. In recent years, we\'ve also seen a plethora of command line tools around the NodeJS, Ruby, and Python communities to name a few. Some may argue that the command line is perfect the way it is, and yet others disagree.</p>', NULL, '2016-07-27 15:27:10', '2016-07-27 15:56:27', '45042490-9f2e-440e-821c-d37aa080251b'),
 ('21', '49', 'en_us', 'Enter HyperTerm', NULL, NULL, '2016-07-27 15:47:23', '2016-07-27 15:56:27', 'aee79a80-b600-47c2-a01b-8a41451f7d51'),
 ('22', '50', 'en_us', NULL, '<p>HyperTerm is a unique solution to the problem of extending the potential of the command line. It\'s built with Electron\'s own blend of HTML, CSS, and JavaScript, which makes it accessible to a much larger portion of the developer population that isn\'t experienced with native application development. Github already did this with their own Atom text editor, and proved that applications built with web technologies can be just as fast and performant as their native counterparts. Just like Atom, HyperTerm can be easily plugged into and extended to do anything that the web can do. If you can build the extension, HyperTerm can emulate it. Packages, plugins and themes are already flowing in at a fast pace, and with more than 6,000 stars on Github since it\'s release almost two weeks ago, the packages are only going to keep flowing in and growing in number. I\'ve even contributed a theme and zsh configuration for it myself, and I\'ve got a few more plugins in the works.</p>\n\n<p>The best part of HyperTerm, to me is the possibility to take a tool that I use for hours on end every day and extend it into the perfect productivity tool for my development workflow.</p>', NULL, '2016-07-27 15:47:23', '2016-07-27 15:56:27', 'adac5fe2-e584-4d17-a9c2-ce7334d9b5c1');



